args:
Chelle invites Leif to a game of Alberian Chess.
Suspicious of the princess, Leif offers words of
warning to the prince, who heads off to a mine
at Jupiter's suggestion. There, the group is
surprised to find a number of nesting fiends,
and quickly readies for battle.
The Radiant City, Chanzelia.\nThe evening after the welcome party.
I would have you spend the evening\nwith me, my dear Leif.

After that splendid party, some
quality time together would be
just the thing for us—perhaps
with a dash of competition?
Alberian Chess? Interesting. It's been\nsome time since we last matched wits\nin the capital.
You are in for a rude shock indeed\nif you think the outcome will be\nthe same as it was back then!
Well then, let's see what you can do.
My first move is to upset your line with\nmy woodland archers.
Then I shall fortify my position\nwith my grassland warriors.
Your tactics are as small-minded as ever.\nI rout your warriors with my sellswords!

A flashy move is not necessarily an adroit
one, Princess—for as you see, I now have
you surrounded. Tell me, how will you
escape this particular predicament?
Well? Will you force your way through\nregardless of the casualties you receive?
That is certainly what the OLD me would\nhave done—fight to the very last man,\neven if it leads to my destruction.
But a girl does not remain one forever.
First, I flank you with my stone trebuchet.\nThen, using the cover it provides, I move\nmy sorcerer princess forward.

Clever? Impressive? All that and more?
I have changed, Leif. I am no longer
an impetuous young girl, but instead a
gorgeous maiden of depth and character.

If it were necessary, I would not even
hesitate to take a step backward so
I might later take two steps forward
and obtain an ultimate victory.
Your development is remarkable;\nyour impulsiveness of old is nowhere\nto be found.
Eee hee hee! Oh, I think you can do\nbetter than that on the praise front.
Ah, but praise must be earned, Princess.\nNow, how will you respond when I\nmove my sacred dragonlord forward?
And that is checkmate. It seems you are\nnot the only one who has improved.
Ah, but that is utterly vexing; I thought\nfor sure today was the day I would wipe\nthat eternal composure from your face.
You say as much, and yet you do not\nLOOK especially vexed.
It is disgraceful to betray one's emotions.
I noticed you stopped doing so.
There was once a time when I feared\nyour fiery passions might cause you to\nrise up and strike me full in the face.
Yet now, beneath that mask of pleasure-\nseeking, you hide a multitude of faces.
Where, I wonder, does your true heart lie?
Who was it that wounded my heart with\na blade as sharp as the one at your hip?
That ＂true heart＂ of mine disappeared\nthat day.
Eee hee! Do not fear, Sparrow—\nI bear no grudge. I learned well from you.
You taught me not to be deceived by my\neyes—and to keep what I cherish most\ntucked safely away.
But let us stop speaking of the past and\ninstead engage in another round.
And yet morning has not arrived.
A lady does not show her vexation\nopenly just because she lost a game.
But a lady also does not end her night\ncloaked in the stench of defeat!
I will not withdraw at this point. Not now.
Is something wrong, Leif?\nYou look troubled.
Ah, Your Majesty. I suppose I'm a bit\nconcerned about the princess.
I find myself unable to determine her\nmotives, and feel it could be a grave error\nto simply accept her words at face value.
How do I put this... It is almost as if...
She and I are cut from the same cloth.\nI...understand her.
Even when her face is calm, the thoughts\nin her head race like a whirlwind.
I like that about her. I like it very much.
So you think she's plotting something?\nBut what? And why?
Perhaps you would understand better if\nyou got a personal look at the source of\nthe power that supports Chanzelia.
You mean to take him to—
The materium mine? Yes, that is exactly\nwhat I intend to do.
I feel the presence of a strange mana\nemanating from the ruins at the outskirts\nof this fair city.
They're excavating relics at the mine,\nso there ought to be workers there\nwho we can question.
Then we'll leave first thing in the morning.
No. We should visit the mine under\nthe cover of night—THIS night.
If we are found, things might\nbecome...problematic.
The hell's goin' on here, boss?!
There ain't no workers here—\nit's just a crapload'a fiends!
I don't know, Ranzal. But if these are\nno ordinary ruins as Jupiter suspects...
Then perhaps we can learn the princess's\nmotives if we descend into their depths.
And if she IS plottin' something,\nwe'll find it, beat the crap outta it,\nand send her smug face packin'!
